- "very high" means greater than 0.8 for average accuracy and greater than 0.9 for confidence level; 
- "high" means greater than 0.7 for average precision; 
- "relatively fast" means less than 10 for average computational time; 
- "relatively low" means less than 1000 for average memory usage and less than 50 for average CPU usage.

- 'DETECTOR_1', 'DESCRIPTOR_1', and 'MATCHER_1' refer to specific types of algorithms used in object detection and tracking systems. These could be referring to highly specialized algorithms designed for high accuracy and speed in certain environments or conditions;
- LIDAR (Light Detection and Ranging) and camera sensors are commonly used in robotic and autonomous systems for detecting and tracking objects. LIDAR sensors provide accurate distance measurements, while cameras offer visual data for object identification;
- Time-to-Collision (TTC) is a critical metric in autonomous systems, representing the time before a potential collision might occur. It is calculated based on the relative speed and distance between the system and detected objects;
- Performance metrics such as accuracy, precision, computational time, memory usage, and CPU usage are essential for evaluating the efficiency and effectiveness of the algorithm combinations in real-world applications.
